Bicalutamide has an extremely long half-life and therefore takes a considerable amount of time before it reaches steady-state serum levels. However on the other hand, it's a ludicrously powerful androgen receptor antagonist with absurdly high binding affinity, and 50 mg is a fairly high dose for MTF HRT use.

You can cold turkey the spiro if you want, but if you do, you'll probably see at least some signs of reduced androgen receptor blockade for a couple of weeks. This may or may not be a concern depending on your personal preferences.

Alternatively, you could overlap them for perhaps 2–4 weeks, which should ensure adequate androgen blockade is maintained. A risk with this approach though is that you may start seeing too much effective T suppression. One thing you can try is taking e.g. 100 mg spiro for the first week or two, then dropping down to 50 mg for another week or two before eliminating it entirely.

I'm going to assume you're already aware of the usual special considerations to be aware of regarding T level lab test results on bicalutamide, and that you're also aware of the critical importance of routine liver function lab panels while taking this drug.
